{"type":"message","id":"ffea30a2","parentId":"ca02199f","timestamp":"2026-02-19T09:49:58.407Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"I found the sheet information. The \"Inventory\" sheet has sheetId: 592229113. I can now use the batch command to insert a row at row 58 (which is after row 57, so I need to insert at index 57 because the API is 0-indexed and I want to insert before row 58).\n\nWait, let me think about this more carefully. If I want to insert a row after row 57, that means I want to insert at row 58. In the Google Sheets API:\n- Row indices are 0-based\n- To insert a new row, I use the `insertDimension` request\n- `startIndex` is where the insertion starts\n- `endIndex` is where the insertion ends (exclusive)\n\nSo if I want to insert a row at row 58 (after row 57), I would use:\n- startIndex: 57\n- endIndex: 58\n\nThis would insert 1 row at position 57 (which is row 58 in 1-based indexing).\n\nBut actually, I think the user might want to just append a row at the end, or maybe they want to insert at a specific position. Let me re-read the request.\n\n\"append a dummy record in inventory after row 57\"\n\nThis could mean:\n1. Insert a new row between row 57 and row 58\n2. Append the record at the end of the sheet (after row 57 in the sense that row 57 is the last data row)\n\nLooking at the info output, I can see the Inventory sheet has rowCount: 1073, which suggests it has many rows already. The table \"Unit_Availability_Details\" has endRowIndex: 57, which means the formal table ends at row 56 (0-indexed).\n\nI think the user wants to insert a row at row 58 (1-based), which would be after row 57 (1-based). This would mean inserting at index 57 (0-based).\n\nLet me create a batch request to insert a row and then write the data to it.","thinkingSignature":"reasoning"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_ba4d","name":"write","arguments":{"path":"C:\\Users\\MudasserRasool\\.openclaw\\workspace\\skills\\google-sheets-api\\batch-